article.headline: New Mexico 79, New Mexico State 76
article.story: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico guard Darren Prentice's patience is finally paying off. The former Alamogordo High School star spent much of his first two seasons at New Mexico on the bench, unsure of his role, uncertain if he'd ever get a chance to show what he could do. All of that's changing this season. Prentice still hasn't broken into the starting lineup, but he's made a big impact on New Mexico's 5-0 mark, the Lobos' best start since the 1998-99 season. The slick and quick guard matched his career high with 16 points and consistently made big shots and key free throws in New Mexico's 79-76 win over New Mexico State on Tuesday night. "I didn't feel more pressure, rather more focus," Prentice said of his sterling effort in the state's biggest rivalry game. "I knew the Aggies were going to come in strong and I had the confidence in myself. I was waiting for my time." Prentice got plenty of help in New Mexico's latest win, from his teammates and from the Aggies (1-3), who self-destructed at the free throw line in a game they had plenty of chances to win. J.R. Giddens scored 19 points and Aaron Johnson grabbed 14 rebounds for New Mexico, which led by 16 points late in the first half, then had to hold off a tenacious rally by the Aggies over the final 20 minutes. "This is the kind of game where you've got to be a man and stay in there and fight," said Johnson, who added 10 points. "The tougher team wins and we were tougher at the end." New Mexico State missed three 3-point shots in the final 19 seconds. But it wouldn't have come down to the long-range shots if the Aggies had been able to hit free throws. They missed 12 in the second half and hit just 12 of 28 in the game. The Aggies also missed several lay-ups "I didn't know I was going to have to teach lay-ups and free throws," said New Mexico State second-year coach Reggie Theus. The Aggies not only had to deal with a tough loss, but also the wrath of Theus, who promised he'd have the Aggies shooting free throws once they got back to Las Cruces -- a three-hour ride by bus. "If it hurts me, I'm going to make it hurt them," Theus said. Center Martin Iti led the Aggies' futility at the foul line, missing all eight free throws he took, six of them in the second half. Still the Aggies, who got 23 points from Justin Hawkins and 15 points from reserve guard Ted Knauber on five 3-pointers, had a chance to at least force overtime. The Aggies were within 55-53 with 10:32 left after Iti scored six straight points inside. The Aggies kept the pressure on to the very end, but kept missing free throws and open shots. "We had a great second half, but who cares," Theus said. "We had a very interesting halftime. It took that type of effort and that type of heart. That type of heart wasn't there in the first half." Freshman point guard Jamaal Smith hit two free throws to give New Mexico a 79-76 lead with 22.1 seconds remaining. The Aggies took a time-out, then freed up Fred Peete for a 3 from the right side that missed. The Aggies rebounded the miss and Hawkins misfired on a 3-pointer from the left baseline. Giddens was fouled with 5.7 seconds remaining, but he missed both free throws. With the clock winding down, Aggie freshman Jonathan Gibson put up a 3-pointer that was long as the buzzer sounded. New Mexico led through most of the game and built a 44-28 lead with 29 seconds left in the first half on the shooting of Tony Danridge and Prentice. Danridge scored 11 straight points in one stretch and by halftime had matched his career high of 15 points. He was 7-for-7 in the first half but took just two shots in the second half. Prentice hit 5 of 6 shots and had 3 3-pointers. He halted an early second half NMSU run with a hook shot in the lane and later banked in a shot over his defender after the Aggies had closed to within 70-67. His two free throws with 2:19 remaining gave New Mexico a 75-71 lead and after Giddens hit a 12-footer, the Lobos led 77-71 with a minute left. But the Aggies weren't done. Hawkins hit a 3 with 41.7 seconds left and Iti a layup with 22.6 seconds remaining to get the Aggies within 77-76. Johnson finished with a double-double by scoring 10 points.
